Disk Forensics > [T5]: Exploring NTFS Master File Table

(1) $MFT

Master File Table ($MFT) is a database that tracks all objects (files and folders) changes on an NTFS filesystem. Each object (file/folder) has its own record in the $MFT file, containing metadata about that file. 

$MFT file is stored in the root of the NTFS partition (i.e., C:\). To access it on a disk/triage image you acquired earlier, load it into FTK Imager, and you will find it under the [root] folder, which represents the drive root.

 

$MFT file - (zoom in)

  1. Drive root
  2. $MFT file

To explore the content of the $MFT file, use "R-studio".

Our tool of choice to extract and parse $MFT file content is "MFTEcmd," which produces a CSV file that can be viewed using the famous "Timeline Explorer."

 

 

mft.csv in Timeline Explorer - (zoom in)

  1. The entry number will be used later to cross reference records between $MFT and $USNJRNL (explained later in the lesson).
  2. Parent Entry Number: usually contains the parent folder where the file resides.
  3. In use: if this field is unchecked, it's a deleted object. The value in the "Last Record Change" column will indicate when the object was deleted.
  4. Parent Path: contain the location of the file.
  5. File name.
  6. File extension.
  7. The "Is directory" field will be checked if the object is a folder, not a file.
  8. Has Ads: indicates if this object contains Alternate Data Streams. Alternate Data Stream (ADS) is an NTFS file system feature that allows a file to store multiple different data streams in addition to the default stream, normally used for a file. This feature was created to allow Windows to read the macOS HFS file system. Attackers can use ADS to create additional streams to hide some data that will not be visible by opening the original file.
  9. "Is Ads": Each file can have multiple streams. Each stream will have its record in $MFT. This field will be checked if this is an ADS stream. 
  10. File size. If this record belongs to a folder, the size will be 0.
  11. Created0x10: indicate the creation date. 
  12. The rest of the timestamps (Access, Modification) are next to the Created0x010 column. Note that you will find two columns of MAC timestamps, "Created0x10" and "Created0x30". The "Created0x30" is for usage with Windows kernel.
